title: The Nasty Lunch
author: jenna
text: one day at the crack of dawn,  i woke up with a spine-tingling start.  i had to get ready for school today,  stopping once for some strawberry tarts.  i rushed down the stairs pel-mel,  then i tripped and i stumbled,  and fell.  my mom was not home,  so i packed lunch on my own,  hoping the food would cook well.   then i heard the bus roaring even over my dadâ’s snoring,  snatching my schoolbooks,  getting ready to go.  i almost missed the bus,  but not my brother gus,  and i got covered in slushy snow.   when i arrived at school,   i did not feel cool,  and my teacher said i was a mess.  the school day was boring,  and i started snoring.  i had lots of trouble on my test.  then…finally! hooray!  iâ’ve been through half the school day! now it is time for lunch.  iâ’m so hungry that i may explode,  i canâ’t wait to munch,  munch,  munch!  when i opened my lunchbox i was very surprised--my hotdog had become rubberized! then i spilt my pudding,  causing me to lose my footing and that yucky pudding got in my eye.   everyone said,  â“eeeeeeeewwwwww!!! you canâ’t sit at our table,  your food is making us sick!  we really do like you,  but do us a favor-â– donâ’t sit with us,  how â‘bout nick?''  so i did what they said,  packing up,  and moving quick.  and then i sat with nick.  he just shook my hand and said,  â“how do you do?â” boy i felt like giving myself a kick.  then i looked at his lunch,  no longer wanting to munch,  and his seemed much worse than mine… it was a one-of-a-kind,  smells-as-bad-as-rotten-rind,  donâ’t-want-to-keep-it-in-mind,  pure pile of junk.  it was full of lumps,  and clumps,  and warty bumps.  he said,  â“boy i hate it when my mum packs lunchâ”.   i thought,  â“wow! his mum packed that lunch?â”  and then i thought of my mom eating out,  having brunch.  i said to him,  â“you know,  maybe you should pack your food.  but i did it this morning,  and now iâ’m in a bad moodâ”.   everything went horribly wrong that day.  oh,  how i wish my mom wasnâ’t away--.

title: In The Old Days
author: jill
text: in the old days  in the old days.   they had diners with waitresses on roller blades and food on big trays.  they had the juke boxes and padded seats to sit on and listen to the cool beats.  at some places they had drive-ins.  with workers that wore uniforms and pepsi pins.  they had hambergs and hot dogs that were so big they looked like loges.  there was root beer floats in big mugs.  people could come to the drive-in in their cars such as the volkswagon bugs.  it seemed that it was cooler back then with skating around in a restaurant and being able to drive-in.  i think it was and i donâ’t know why things have changed but so to the good times we have to say good bye.

title: Kids In The Spring
author: jill
text: kids in the spring\tby jill sweezy  spring is the perfect time of the year.  the sun is out and summer is near.  the winter is gone.  iâ’m so happy all i want to do is sing a song.  i see all the kids out to play.  i look out my window and they play all day.  they never stop.  they just go on to hop.  sometimes they fall and drop.  they sure do make a lot of noise.  iâ’m getting confused with all these little girls and boys.  before you know it they are all outside.  screaming and yelling and running around.  sometimes they stay still and donâ’t make a sound.  the snow and ice are gone.  and all these little kids are singing songs.

title: Slobbery Spinach
author: jill
text: here he comes.  my dad with that buttery,  salty,  no flavor spinach.  ready for me to eat.  but i hate it,  it smells like dirty,  old feet.  he came up the stairs.  he tripped and fell and spinach went everywhere.  my dog ate some licked me and spread it all over my head.  i ran as if i was in a race.  with all this gross,  degusting,  slobbery spinach all over my face.

title: The weekend
author: jill
text: on the weekend i have a lot of fun.  looking up at the bright blue  sky and the shinning sun.  i love to go outside on a hot day.  on the weekend all i do is play.  i play with my short,  little,  hairy  dog.  sometimes she licks my face.  we run,  play ball,  and race.  now it is the weekend and iâ’m going out to play.  bye iâ’m going to be out all day.

title: School's Out
author: jill
text: schoolâ’s out!!  schoolâ’s out,  everyone is here to shout.  this is what it is all about.  jumping,  racing,  having fun.  running around,  looking at the sun.  no more homework,  no more school work.  but you still have to eat your veggies mixed with chunks of pork.  and still have to do your chores.  and still have to get ready for the next year.  but the spring is here and the summer is near.  enjoy it while you can.  run around with your friends and bang on pots and pans.
